==English==
From Latin [[inflammare]] with the suffix ''-able''. [[inflammare]] comes from [[in]] + [[flamma]] with te suffix ''-are''. It means that something has the flame ([[flamma]]) within ([[in]]).
===Pronunciation===
*ĭnʹflăm-ə-bəl, /ɪnˈflæməbəl/, /<tt>In"fl{m@b@l</tt>/

===Adjective===
'''inflammable'''
# Capable of burning; easily set on fire.

====Usage notes====
*'''Inflammable''' can be misinterpreted as an [[antonym]] of  '''flammable''' and so taken to have the opposite meaning to that intended. Where such confusion might arise, especially where this may be a safety hazard, it is preferable to use a [[synonym]].

====Synonyms====
*[[burnable]]
*[[combustible]]
*[[flammable]]

====Antonyms====
*[[fireproof]]
*[[incombustible]]
*[[non-flammable]]
*[[non-inflammable]]
*[[unburnable]]

